What could be wrong with my patch?
`if (CB.getType()->isTokenTy()) return;`
This seems correct. It prevents GVN from processing calls that return a token. The `target(...)` type is likely being treated as a token.

Maybe the issue is more subtle. Let's re-read the IR.
`%buf = tail call target("dx.RawBuffer", i32, 1, 0) @llvm.dx.resource.handlefrombinding(...)`
The type is `target("dx.RawBuffer", i32, 1, 0)`. This is a scalable vector type in disguise for DirectX. It's not exactly `token`. The `isTokenTy()` check might be too specific.

Let's look for how LLVM identifies these special DirectX types. They are often handled as `token` types conceptually, but maybe the `Type` object itself doesn't report `isTokenTy()`.

The error is "PHI nodes cannot have token type!". This strongly suggests that somewhere along the line, the type is considered a token. The verifier is the one complaining. Let's look at the verifier logic. `llvm/lib/IR/Verifier.cpp`.

Searching for "PHI nodes cannot have token type!" in `Verifier.cpp`:
```cpp
// Check that a PHI node has at least one incoming value.
// Check that all incoming values are of the same type as the PHI node.
// Check that all incoming values are not token type.
if (PN->getNumIncomingValues() == 0)
  CheckFailed("PHI node has no incoming values!", PN);
for (Value *V : PN->incoming_values()) {
  if (V->getType() != PN->getType())
    CheckFailed("PHI node operands are not the same type as the result!",
                PN, V);
  if (V->getType()->isTokenTy())
    CheckFailed("PHI nodes cannot have token type!", PN, V);
}
```
The check is `V->getType()->isTokenTy()`. So my assumption that the type is a token type is correct, at least from the verifier's perspective.

So why did my patch not work?
`sed -i '/void GVN::processCall(CallBase &CB) {/a\  if (CB.getType()->isTokenTy())\n    return;' llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp`
